Here is a script for you to update `persistent_peers` setting in `config.toml`. Stale peers can cause node inefficiency over time, so the script below selects a few random live peers.

```bash
PEERS=3088c54f42f52e0288ad46b0e3c66e475c6c19a8@65.109.33.25:26656,77fc93e9ae71eeb4675647c5fd655820c50f1126@144.76.58.185:26656,2fba2855815114b4ec9d40e73d9579cbb07d7cf6@5.223.48.129:26656,47987080e86e0b5dda26cd9be1c1677f00c46dcd@5.75.149.205:26656,fe7873a8c6c4e2bda68a53c83d35fbf52016441c@185.119.118.110:2000
sed -i.bak -e "s/^persistent_peers *=.*/persistent_peers = \"$PEERS\"/" ~/.osmosisd/config/config.toml

sudo systemctl restart osmosisd
sudo journalctl -fu osmosisd --no-hostname -o cat
```
